// was called getNextBox(); nicest DDA step function I've seen!
// tiny, simple, completely dynamic, fast.  Clever!
// TODO merge in somehow, try it out; I already rearranged
// it somewhat, eliminated some temp variables used once.
// changed dim (was boxDim) to an argument, etc.  Went back to 2D too.
// Easy enough and good to have both variants in one place. --Sean
// if you want to understand it, I made a 1D version that
// simply uses sign to decide which way to step, plus or minus.
float nextCell(float p, float v, float c) //, float dim)
{ // since step(dt, dt) is equivalent to 1.0, just get rid of now-unused dt.
    float d = sign(v); //, dt = ((c + d * .5) * dim - p) / v;
    return c + d; // * step(dt, dt);
}
// it wound up not needing the dim, so what if none of them used dim?
// I may have *caller* to do such coordinate system conversion/mapping,
// so that the p coordinate here is always already in cell coordinates
// which simplifies a few things
// dim is size of cell hypercubes in p space, they don't have to
// actually be the same size here, for these variants
// which are closer to ocb's originals which were called getNextBox or getNextCell.  
        // see, his may be just little too clever, as it integrates
        // the tracking of the ray position in a way that is incompatible
        // with keeping the same ray and just incrementing the offset along it.
        // I prefer to avoid the accumulation of small errors from individual steps
        // anyway I require new t, or delta to t, distance to the next cell
    // knowing the cell id isn't helping much, for me; I need the distance to hit
    // and, see, his thing is simply not set up to help calculate the needed step distance

// key function to find the next Voxel along the ray
vec2 nextCell(vec2 p, vec2 v, vec2 c, float dim)
{
    vec2 d = sign(v), dt = ((c + d * .5) * dim - p) / v;
    return c + d * step(dt, vec2(min(dt.x, dt.y)));
}
vec3 nextCell(vec3 p, vec3 v, vec3 c, float dim)
{
    vec3 d = sign(v), dt = ((c + d * .5) * dim - p) / v;
    return c + d * step(dt, vec3(min(min(dt.x, dt.y), dt.z)));
}
// p is a current position, c is corresponding id of cell
// which p is currently inside, v is trace direction

//vec2    return c + d * step(dt, vec2(min(dt.x, dt.y)));
//vec3    return c + d * step(dt, vec3(min(min(dt.x, dt.y), dt.z)));
// ocb's scanner was called browseBox and had totally different interface
        //vec3 n = newBox - box; // but his allowed to find the hit normal with little cost!
